Custom Pay Rates
Problem Statement, Strategic Context & Solution Proposal
Strategic Context
At the time of development, the strategic priority for Rentman was clear: enter and win the U.S. market.
The United States represents the largest addressable market in the event and production industry. While strong equipment management tools existed, there was no flexible, state-aware crew planning solution capable of handling the complexity of U.S. labor structures.
Our entry strategy was deliberate:
Lead with a best-in-class Crew Scheduling product tailored to U.S. operational complexity.
Onboard companies through planning workflows.
Expand into Equipment Management and position Rentman as the all-in-one solution.
One recurring blocker — especially in U.S. sales conversations — was Custom Pay Rates:
Overtime rules differ per state
Double time and minimum call rules vary
Union vs. non-union setups coexist
Cost (what you pay crew) and price (what you charge customers) often differ
While similar complexity exists in Germany and Norway, the U.S. market amplified this challenge significantly.
Solving Custom Pay Rates was therefore not just a feature enhancement —
it was a strategic enabler for U.S. market penetration and expansion.

My Role
As Product Manager responsible for Crew Scheduling, I:
