Problem Identification
1. Data Signal: Manual Cost Editing
Before conducting interviews, we observed a strong behavioral signal in our product analytics:
Users frequently edited the cost field manually
These edits often occurred after changing scheduled times
The pattern was especially prominent in U.S.-based accounts
This indicated a clear gap:
Time changes were not triggering automated recalculations in a way that matched customer expectations.
In other words, automation was missing where users needed it most.
The product technically allowed scheduling and rate assignment —
but the recalculation logic was too rigid for real-world overtime structures.
This was our first quantitative validation that something was broken.

2. Interview Validation (U.S. Focus)
We then conducted 10 discovery interviews across multiple countries, with a strong focus on U.S. customers.
Findings:
Project managers were recalculating overtime manually in spreadsheets
They often adjusted crew hours and then manually corrected costs
U.S. state-level variations made this process error-prone
Some companies had internal “rate cheat sheets” to handle complexity
The behavioral data and interviews aligned perfectly.

3. Public Roadmap & Community Validation
We had a third validation point: our public Productboard.
In our public feedback portal, customers could:
Submit feature requests
Vote on roadmap items
Describe operational pain points
Custom Pay Rates consistently ranked among the top-voted requests.
Users described:
Complex regional rules
Union-based multipliers
Minimum call times
Day-rate vs hourly conflicts
This triangulation gave us confidence:
Product data showed heavy manual editing behavior
Interviews explained why
Public roadmap votes confirmed scale and urgency

